description:
Indian Blanket (Gaillardia pulchella)

6 July 2014: While walking the North Lakes Inner Trail at North Lakes Park, Denton, Texas, we came upon a blooming field of different native wildflowers and the one that was most abundant at that site on that day was none other than Indian Blanket (Gaillardia pulchella). Atop one of the flowers rested a Brown Blister Beetle (Epicauta immaculata) that seemed to be feeding on what the flower had to offer. North Lakes Park is administered by the City of Denton, Texas.

Source: For a gallery of images and description of Indian Blanket go to the Lady Bird Johnson Wildflower Center here: http://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=GAPU

These things are thick and in the mix with some blue bonnets. It looks really pretty from afar. It looks very nice out there. These centers are pretty interesting too. I haven't seen as many of these this year as in previous years. There has been many popping up around school and the surrounding area.

description: I'm uploading these images of standard Indian Blankets to use as a reference for a journal ID article. For the record, note: -- Disk flowers with medusa-like tangles of long hairs (close-up in 2nd image); -- Phyllaries with numerous long hairs, especially on edges (3rd image). Both these characters will separate this species from the somewhat similar Gaillardia coahuilensis that occurs in s.w. Texas (primarily Crockett, Kinney, Terrell, and Val Verde counties). Compare to: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/12577376 I wrote a short journal article about this and I've tried to add a link to on the Bandana Daisy species page. https://www.inaturalist.org/journal/gcwarbler/16792-identifying-bandana-daisy-in-southwest-texas

description:
This bright fiery red-orange organism has tips a sunny yellow with a brownish red center that fades into a faint lime green in the middle. It has approximately ten 1-inch petals all with two or three ridges per petal and vertical stripes running down to the center. These petals form around the core, creating a circular dimension. Each organism is devoid of leaves up to nearly the base of the flower. Near the base there are a cluster of leaves seemingly to support the flower. The flower was found not far from the Hillsborough river in a sandy terrain. There was little shade to protect the flowers, the sun was out at the time the picture was taken, and the temperature was around 68 degrees Fahrenheit. There were only a handful of these flowers scattered about as the sandy terrain they thrive off of were only in patches. What makes these organisms distinct is there stunning coloration. The flowers all possess the same radiant colors attracting bees and other insect to spread their pollen. These flowers can be found throughout North America, but primarily in dry terrains with calcareous soil . This organism belongs to Kingdom Plantae, Clade Angiosperms, Clade Eudicots, Clade Asterids, Order Asterales, Family Asteraceae, Genus Gaillardia, and Species Pulchella. 

Reference: https://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=GAPU

description: This observation was taken at 12:22 pm near a sidewalk in Weedon Island preserve. It was very sunny and very hot out (~30 degrees Celsius). I identified this by comparing characteristics with other plants on there Florida Native Plant Society (https://www.fnps.org/plants/plant/gaillardia-pulchella ). This species is native to North America and it is commonly found throughout the United States.

The three middle photos (4,5,6) were added on 3-May-2019, after finding two flowers in bloom.  Other specimens with "mostly red" rays (like this one) were seen in nearby blocks, growing in and around the more-typical "red and yellow" pattern typical of G. pulchella. The six right-most photomicrographs are courtesy of Pete Romfh (each cross-hatch line represents 1mm, darkest lines are 1cm), posted here on 20-May-2019.  Of the six, the left three are cypsalae (seeds) from the inner portion (center) of the seed head, while the right three are from the outer edge.

The genus for this flower would be Gaillardia, and is mostly grown in the summer/fall time. ( https://www.gardenia.net/plant-variety/gaillardia-blanket-flower)
